# [cite_start]xv6-Auth Login & User Management [cite: 1]

## Overview
[cite_start]This project extends the inherently single-user xv6 operating system to support multiple users, secure login authentication, and user privilege management[cite: 8, 9]. [cite_start]It includes a password hashing utility to ensure user credentials are securely stored[cite: 11].

## [cite_start]Team Members [cite: 3]
* [cite_start]CS23B1044 - Nimalan R [cite: 4]
* [cite_start]CS23B1065 - Nithyanand R [cite: 5]
* CS23B1075 - K.V.S. [cite_start]Jayadheer [cite: 6]

## System Architecture & Features
* [cite_start]The `struct proc` was modified to include an integer `uid` field to track user IDs[cite: 14, 15].
* [cite_start]The Root user is assigned UID 0[cite: 16].
* [cite_start]Standard users are assigned UIDs greater than 0[cite: 17].
* [cite_start]User credentials are saved in a `users` file, which is burned into the file system image (`fs.img`) during compilation via a modified `mkfs` to ensure persistence across reboots[cite: 18, 19].
* [cite_start]Introduced a `sys_getuid` system call that returns the current process's UID[cite: 21, 22].
* [cite_start]Introduced a `sys_setuid` system call that sets the UID of the current process[cite: 21, 23].
* [cite_start]The system initialization loop in `init.c` was modified to fork and execute the `login` program instead of the shell, forcing authentication before a user can access the shell[cite: 207, 208].

## User-Space Utilities
* [cite_start]**`login`**: Prompts for a username and password, validates them against the `users` file, calls `setuid`, and executes the shell[cite: 382].
* [cite_start]**`adduser`**: Allows creating new users by appending credentials to the `users` file[cite: 383].
* [cite_start]**`whoami`**: Prints the currently logged-in user's name and UID[cite: 384].
* [cite_start]**`su`**: Verifies a password and allows a user to switch their profile and UID to another account (like root)[cite: 385].
* [cite_start]**`hashpw`**: A standalone C program run on the host machine to generate the initial hashed password database[cite: 386].

## Building and Running

**1. Generate Password Database**
[cite_start]First, compile the helper tool on your host machine to create the initial `users` file[cite: 390]:
`bash
gcc -o hashpw hashpw.c
./hashpw root root 0 > users
`

**2. Compile and Boot xv6**
`bash
make clean && make qemu
`
[cite_start]*(Note: Compiling and booting can be done with this single command [cite: 401])*

**3. Login**
[cite_start]The system will boot and prompt `init: starting login`[cite: 403].
[cite_start]You can enter `root` as the login and `root` as the password to access the system[cite: 405, 408, 409].